statement.p:
For a temperature field u, the heat equation with constant diffusivity
\alpha\gt 0 is
\boxed{u_t=\alpha\Delta u.}
In one space dimension,
\boxed{u_t=\alpha u_{xx}.}
In two space dimensions,
\boxed{u_t=\alpha(u_{xx}+u_{yy}).}
In three space dimensions,
\boxed{u_t=\alpha(u_{xx}+u_{yy}+u_{zz}).}

subsection.p:
The term
\frac{s}{c}
is the temperature increase forced by the source.

statement.p:
The wave equation in one space dimension is
\boxed{u_{tt}=c^2u_{xx}.}
In two space dimensions, the wave equation is
\boxed{u_{tt}=c^2\Delta u=c^2(u_{xx}+u_{yy}).}
In three space dimensions,
\boxed{u_{tt}=c^2\Delta u=c^2(u_{xx}+u_{yy}+u_{zz}).}

subsection.p:
The wave equation is second order in time. That is one visible difference between heat and
waves:
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
\text{Equation} \amp \text{Time derivative} \amp \text{Behavior} \\ \hline
u_t=\alpha\Delta u \amp \text{first order} \amp \text{spreads and smooths}\\[1mm]
u_{tt}=c^2\Delta u \amp \text{second order} \amp \text{travels and oscillates}
\end{array}

statement.p:
A twice differentiable function u satisfies Laplace's equation if
\boxed{\Delta u=0.}
In the plane,
\boxed{u_{xx}+u_{yy}=0.}
In space,
\boxed{u_{xx}+u_{yy}+u_{zz}=0.}
A function satisfying Laplace's equation is called harmonic.
